s an anthropologist whose fieldwork has taken her to the devastated worlds of her parents-to Korea and to the Korean language-allowing her, as she explains, to find and found kinship relationships that had been suppressed or broken in war and illness. A fascinating counterpoint to the project of testimony that seeks to transmit a narrative of the event to future generations, Seeing Like a Child sees the inheritance of familial memories of violence as embedded in how the child inhabits her everyday life.Seeing Like a Child offers readers a unique experience-an intimate engagement with the emotional reality of migration and the inheritance of mass displacement and death-inviting us to explore categories such as "catastrophe," "war," "violence," and "kinship" in a brand-new light.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChildren and war. 0aKorean War, 1950-1953. 0aKoreanszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aChild.  aEveryday.  aInheritance.  aKorea.  aKorean War.  aLanguage.  aMemory.  aOrdinary.1 aRechtman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRechtman, Richard.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311072271040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823289486zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn